NOSTALGICO DEMO

----------------------------------------------------------------------
                                                          cih/requiem
----------------------------------------------------------------------

CIH's VIEWPOINT:


We get down and dirty on an STFM of neolithic vintage, complete with a 
case that sort of wobbles off with a tired sigh, and sparks fly from 
the TV adaptor! Will we get to see the whole demo before this machine 
gives up completely, will there be both pictures and sound at the same 
time? Just what is going on with this 'revival' of the ST megademo 
anyway? 

Now read on....

No-one ever believed that this demo would be finished.. We've been 
waiting long enough, and it isn't as if there was a real big amount of 
news from the web pages over the past year (Leonard, thanks for the 
news you did give us though..)

With a lack of enthusiam killing the 'Resurrection' demo, all hopes for 
a decent 'blast from the past' project were firmly pinned on this 
production, and it was with some interest, that we started to hear 
tales around Xmas time, that this demo was finally nearing completion..

Well, give or take a few weeks, it is here now, was it worth the wait?

It took a bit of scratching around to find that old STFM, covered under 
all those layers of discarded magazines, a moment of initial panic when 
a black blank screen appeared on switching on, a momentary pause to 
reassure myself that is was due to a sad and bedraggled looking monitor 
cable which is nearly bent in two.. Only when I made the trip to Mr 
Pink's place, were we able to borrow a television lead to get a useful 
picture from this box..

Switching on produces a real 'Nostalgic-O' feeling, as an almost pixel-
perfect copy of the Union Demo loader screen kicks in!

Waving it away, a stunning Niko painted 'Oxygene' logo is displayed.. 
Wonder if that guy ever tried to realise his pixellated creations in a 
more solid medium like sculpture? The intro loads, and this is rather 
wonderful.. In common with another French bit of the demo, which we 
shall see a bit later, it is definitely one of the highlights..

Leonard has come up with an 'EKO'-like 3-D screen, an ace looking walk 
through of a futuristic cityscape.. This goes into vector line mode 
momentarily for a credits infoburst, then back to the solid 3-D main 
event, and is a neat way of kicking off proceedings.. From the 'info' 
screen in the demo, a little bit of sneakiness around a PC led to this 
cool screen..

There is a more modern loader for the main menu and the rest of the 
screens, a hyperactive 'dot-rave' loader/depacker..

The main menu is apparently the most impressive ever done on an ST.. 
The screen window is 448 x 256 pixels, and the rendered metallic 
'Charly' sprite is 64 x 80 pixels in size.. From his appearance, maybe 
he shouldn't be considered in the same warm and affectionate light as 
the Union Demo character, but more as a 'Terminator Charly'! I 
personally liked the main menu graphics and system, other people may 
differ on that?

There is a back-up text only main menu, which cuts down on the 
searching around part, clearly inspired by Delta Force's proclamation 
on the subject ("Thou shalt have a simple back-up system to the main 
graphically based menu, as it is a bugger trying to find your way to 
all the screens..")

Just a case of going to the nearest door, and going in..

The first screen is one to gladden the heart of any old-style ST coding 
purist who gave up on the scene when 'Design' started to make an 
appearance.. This is a dots demo.. Lots of them onscreen..In fact 6475 
of them! Followed by a screen of controllable sinus dots with 1250 
onscreen.. A real good old 'Beat dis' screen, as people used to say.. A 
nice little overscan screen with some textual credits brings this part 
of the show to a close..

The next screen we come across continues this seeming plummet back in 
time, with the 'tradition' screen, by the Bad Brew Crew.. Crazy 
thoughts of that long hot summer of 1990, Sammy Joe, armpit farting 
noise competitions between the different members of the Lost Boys, and 
much more from that strange period, all come lurching back!

Onscreen, we get a big sprite, and parallax background, with some nice 
floaty BBC style chip music.. It's as if the last nine years since the 
Mindbomb demo never happened!

Another one from T.O.Y.S. attempts to bring the story up to date by a 
few years, with a central window concentrating on rotating and zooming 
chunky pixels, and a whole bunch of oldish looking graphics surrounding 
it..

In the rough order we looked at the demo, Leonard's fractal engine is 
up next for consideration.. This was clearly inspired by BMT's 'Cray II 
emulator', but, of course, is just that little bit quicker!

A witty screen by the 'Atari Boys' is next.. This takes a slightly 
subversive look at the convention of the gradually building, 'This 
looks boring, but wait to see what comes next' chunky scroller.. The 
scroller mutates into several different shades of puke-making panic, 
the background develops some strange textures, going into ULM demo 
territory at one stage.. The most interesting bits of the text, ie. How 
to make the effect, are very difficult to distinguish from the 
background, and blur in and out of it..

You need sunglasses, with anti-solar eclipse polaroid filters, to read 
this sucker!

The climax of this bit, is when the dots of the background textures, 
mutate into hundreds of tiny little Lemmings, who wave about for a bit, 
then nuke themselves down off the screen!

The next door opens to the other major highlight of the demo, the 
Overlanders 3-D Texture screen!

It is a proven fact, from ST demo history, that when the Overlanders 
'guest-star' on another crews production, they are really launching a 
takeover bid for it! Consider the Pendragons megademo, the three most 
memorable screens were all OVR productions.. What about the European 
demos, frankly a lot of middle ranking screens, a certain amount of 
dross to fill the corners, but the three or four really good screens in 
there, again, mainly by the Overlanders!

Fortunately, this demo proves to be no exception, with this truly 
excellent (and stuffed to the gills) production!

This starts off with a simple textured cube, which rotates around to 
show several different graphics on each face.. The odd character from 
South Park gets in there.. After a time, a flame-plasma 'dissolve' 
effect banishes the cube, and the next object comes onto the screen.. 
This is a starfighter, which flies around for a while, before being 
succeeded by a slightly blocky 'Kryten' style textured head..

A shiny golden star flaunts itself on the screen, making the best use 
of the sixteen available colours, a 'Lucky Strike' cigarette packet.. 
(This provoked a grumble from Mr Pink that he was going to do this!) 
They go so far as to spin a house around..

All objects are also lightsourced too.. Just then, OVR turn up the demo 
effect temperature dial up a notch..

The cube seen at the beginning is back, but with rotating and zooming 
textures, (see our 'Syntax' review in this issue for a description of a 
very similar effect.) An ironic version of the head, a skull, complete 
with bulging eyeballs.. A bit of environment mapped wizardry is next, 
with a blue 'morphing' saphhire, and a face that is all over the 
place..

The best really is saved to last, as an animated 'Kenny' object (from 
TV's 'South Park') waves to the crowd as various credits and greeting 
fly over the top of the screen.. Being Kenny, we all know what happens 
to him in (nearly) every episode, and sure enough, it does!

He explodes, with the now famous refrain "Omigod, he killed Kenny!" 
ringing out from the telly speakers.. Well nearly, as "Omigod, this 
killed my ST too!" We find that out the hard way, that this old 'FM is 
implacably hostile to playing samples, and we have to reboot..

The sound from this machine wasn't the same for a long time after that 
either..

Still, probably the best part of the demo, and not one that you're 
going to forget in a hurry either..

Anything after that is a bit of an anti-climax, so I would repeat this 
useful advice to any aspiring ST demo coders, *never* appear in 
anything that has got the Overlanders on the same billing.. Your own 
work will suffer with the comparison!

In this spirit, we get to look at a smart 'clone' of an old Amiga 
(Phenomena) screen, also seen previously on the ST.. This is another 
cube, with moving objects on the surfaces, much simpler than the 
preceding screens, and somewhat dated in comparison.. This is Martin 
Griffiths (Inner Circle) contribution.. To be fair, it never pretended 
to be anything but an old screen..

Another guest screen by Cream next, a simple (Agent T) designed SID-
player screen, playing a selection of the original Commodore 64 SID 
music from the Union Demo.. Familiar to SID fanatics like me, but a 
pleasant surprise to a lot of people who might not have expected this 
sort of thing on a bog-standard STFM..

The next screen is one I really wish I hadn't gone into.. Describing 
itself as a 'Joke' screen, it is a straightforward copy/conversion of 
the TCB Cuddly Demo 'Big scroller and sample' screen.. This had the 
unfortunate consequence of killing off my ST's sound for good.. (At 
least for the remainder of this reviewing session..)

'Sprite Blast' is another screen in the spirit of the first 'dot demo' 
part.. An average looker, but one which was one of the authors 
favourites, being more technically interesting to old time coders.. You 
get a huge sprite and even huger text as it is..

Minor screens..

There is a very useful 'info' screen, which really needs a mouse 
connected.. It has a HTML-style interface, and was very useful to me in 
giving the precise information for parts of this review (heights in 
pixels etc..)

There is also a nice little disk-copy screen, where you can clone 
copies of this demo, in the style of the Union Demo copy screen.. Lots 
of LED-style graphics, indicator bars flying around the place for the 
no doubt interesting sound that we couldn't hear by that time..

Reset screen..

Easiest to reach from the secondary text menu for some reason.. Seemed 
to hang when actually pressing the reset button?

This is a smallish screen, and is a neat twist on the 3-D cube idea, as 
when it gets up close, it is revealed to be made up of hundreds of 
little vector balls (726 in all!)

These then twist about a central axis forever, or at least until you 
switch the rapidly overheating ST off..

-----v-----

In conclusion, we got through the experience (nearly) unscathed, and 
enjoed it hugely.. The first real 'megademo' for the ST in many years, 
the first 'menu' system based demo since Mrs Thatch was kicked into 
touch.. Not quite the first reset demo in a long time, as Cream managed 
to beat them to that, and remain thoroughly modern at the same time..

The demo seemed to split into two distinct ways of approaching its 
subject.. Some parts, notably Leonard's awesome 3-D intro, and the 
Overlanders sublime textured objects, brought the ST bang up to date in 
demo scene terms.. The effects and presentation not out of place on a 
Falcon.. Other parts went for a self-conscious 'Old school' approach 
(Urg, it's that phrase again!) evoking memories of the golden age of 
the old ST scene c.1988-1991..

Some people may pick and choose which bits they preferred, but the 
overall quality, which is the important thing, was very high 
throughout..

Nostalgic-o? Yes, maybe, but with an eye to the future as well!

Ratings..

I'm not really going to try to rate this in a normal sense, as parts of 
this are very old, and would compare poorly with the more 'modern' 
parts of the demo, if a cold, objective reviewing system was used..

It is sufficient to say, it is wonderful, and the best possible 
advertisment for continuing life on the ST in demo terms..

I would have liked it to run on the Falcy, but still, never mind.. 
Maybe someone can have a poke around my old 'FM to get it back to full 
working order, and this demo may well be starring at the Stafford Atari 
Computing Convention in Spring..

 CiH - Feb '99
