( ( ( Nostalgia-O demo ) )  )
  ( (    by Oxygene    ) )

      Explored by
         Richard Davey
      (rich@atari.org)
ˆ
Demo reviews in the past have often been treated in the same manner 
that you might review a game. Ratings based on graphics, music and 
design. But demos are a strictly personal experience, some that move 
you might not do anything for others. What you consider a rather passe 
effect, someone else might stare at in awe and wonder.

It is this uniqueness that defines a demo, that gives it its soul.

Leonards Nostalgia-O- demo has that soul in abundance. It takes you 
somewhere back into the depths of time, when mega demos roamed the 
earth, scrollers slid endlessly by and your status was half defined by 
the amount of "greetings" lists you appeared in.

Some parts of this demo are several years old, some parts of it are 
very new but look several years old! But that is partly the aim behind 
it anyway. Leonard set out to create a classic ST megademo, to break 
some world records and to get guest screens from others in the scene.

After downloading the demo and creating the boot disk, you sit back and 
watch. The opening screen is a classic conversion of the Union demo 
intro, a nice touch indeed. Everything fades to black, the music kicks 
in and the words appear.. "You all think it was a joke". Well, we have 
all known Leonard has been working on this project for some time now, 
lots of people even doubted it would ever be released. Thankfully he 
proved all the skeptics wrong. The fading text leads into a stunning 3D 
world. You fly backwards through a tunnel system, into various rooms, 
outside past buildings, into a space port and around little ships. It's 
colourful, filled vectors. When the credits overlay ontop of the 3D it 
turns into wireframe for a moment. This section in itself looks really 
cool indeed and the TAO music completes a really awesome screen.

Moving on you get to see the loader screen, the first thing you notice 
is that the demo is depacking the data as it's loading. The second 
thing you notice is just how damn fast the data is actually loading! 
This loading system prevails throughout the entire demo and makes what 
could by all rights have been a really tedious part, rather 
entertaining.

The main menu is a full-screen multi directional scroller. You get to 
move this little 3D robot (let's call him Charley!) around with the 
arrow keys. The robot is a huge animated sprite, 64x85 pixels. The 
whole thing is totally fullscreen and fills up every last remaining 
edge of your monitor! It's fluid and scrolls around flawlessly. The 
standard "doors" lead to various screens. Or you can cheat and press 
UNDO to reach a text menu version instead (but don't be so boring!)

The screens in order are as follows:

ˆDots Revenge (Leonard) 

It opens with a really nice Mon picture, it's just a shame it's only in 
black and white. Some might consider this stylish, but to me it makes 
it seem as if it was an image converted from a better resolution and 
colour depth. Eitherway, it's a good picture for sure. Following it are 
no less than 6475 dots. You probably couldn't count them all anyway, 
but Leonard assures us they are there. You get to see a purple screen 
with a load of white dots blasting around the place. They move rather 
gracefully and you get to control them with the Function keys. TAO 
provides a much needed audio trip with it. If it wasn't for the fun you 
can have making your own dot patterns you'll probably leave this screen 
within a few seconds.

ˆSprites Parallax (BBC) 

The Law and Xerud from the BBC slap a giant sprite onto a vivid 
parallax background and shift the whole thing around at quite some 
rate. This has to be the oldest looking screen in the demo but it's a 
brief slice of fun none-the-less. Probably the most interesting part of 
it is to realise that in the "old" days the two effects (big sprite and 
parallax background) would have made screens in their own right!

ˆFractal Blast (Leonard) 

What can we say? It's fractals. Lots of them. Very colourful, very 
large (320x256) and VERY fast indeed. The standard classic mandelbrot 
taking only 2.6 seconds to calculate and display. Easily the fastest 
Fractal routine on the ST ever. Plus they look really great!

ˆLemmings Colourshock (Atari Boys) 

Personally I thought this screen was great. A real trip down memory 
lane. It starts with a large but plain scroller which proclaims the 
classic "lets add some rasters". You know the score already, bit by bit 
the Atari Boys build up the screen. Adding rasters, music, more 
rasters, bouncing rasters, balls, led scroller and finally hundreds of 
little walking lemmings (which they then proceed to nuke). It's a very 
"old style" screen and for that I love it. Remember this Nostaliga demo 
is meant to be just that. What's more is it's in full screen too. Space 
bar takes you to a plain fullscreen hardware scroller that features a 
classic Amiga font in the style of a biscuit! Rather dull after such a 
nice colourful screen.

ˆSIDCOM (Cream) 

This screen is plain, just a logo and a "typewriter" text effect. But 
that's not why you'll spend ages on it - TAO presents you with all of 
the classic tunes used in the Union demo (and in turn converted from 
the C64). He's converted the lot and all 10 tunes are superb and bring 
back fond old memories. Ikari Union, Alloy Run, Ninja Remix et all are 
here in glorious SID format. Listen and love.
ˆ
Guest Joke Screen (TCB!) 

You'll know the screen the moment you see it - the huge bouncing white 
scroller on a distorting blue background with that short but thumping 
"bass" sample. So it's a joke screen (in that TCB didn't actually 
submit it for this demo) but whattaheck!

ˆSprite and Megascroller Blast (Leonard) 

Some well drawn balls (borrowed from the Decade demo) wave around the 
screen to a digi music tune. Then from out of nowhere a massive scroll 
text blasts past. It's a greatly resized Knighthawks font with a raster 
coloured middle. That's about it really - oh, and it's full screen! The 
best part is the quote "Oxygene needs no custom chips to display 
balls!"

ˆ3D Cube (Griff - Inner Circle) 

This is a conversion of a part of Phenomenas classic Enigma demo on the 
Amiga. Maybe Griff had had ideas to convert the whole demo at some 
point? Who knows, it's a shame he never did but this section of it is 
good enough. A small blue square with a star field in it, the square 
turns - you realise its a cube and there are different effects on each 
face. It's smooth, not particularly colourful, is missing the great 
soundtracker tune that was on the original but is a good testament to 
Griffs programming prowess. Sadly though it's very short indeed, the 
screen ending after what seems like only a few seconds.

ˆ3D Mapping (Ben - Overlanders) 

The Overlanders! Yeah! My God they always had style. All those Triton 
Design graphics and logos, the great scrolling menus, the manic 3D 
screens and giant scrollers. Ahhh.. nostalgia! However for this 
contribution they concentrate on one somewhat newer effect - namely 
texture mapping onto 3D objects. However this is pulled off really 
quite well, the objects vary from skulls and faces to paper aeroplanes 
to stars and South Park characters! It's smooth, it actually looks 
quite good considering the limitations and the ending part is brilliant 
(I'll not spoil it for you - just go see it). Most notable of all 
though has to be the soundtrack from Jess. This is easily the best tune 
in the entire Nostalgia-O- demo. Great stuff!

ˆFullscreen Rotozoomer (Toys)

Peylow kicks back and blasts forth some seriously fast effects. 
Colourful twisting backgrounds, multiple vertical scrollers, big 
logos, sprites zipping about and a massive rotozoomer! It's like he 
took 6 of his favourite effects from demos across the years and glued 
them all together into this one (no bordered!) screen. More.. please!

ˆLED Copy Screen (Leonard) 

What true megademo would be complete without a built-in copy system? 
Obviously not this one. Leonard has gone LED scroller mad and this 
screen will actually copy the demo for you too, what a bargain. I'm 
also happy to see some VU meters in the screen! No megademo should be 
complete without VU meters (sorry evil!)
ˆ
Credits Screen (Leonard) 

Very cleverly this screen uses an HTML style interface. Various words 
lead onto other screens, all laid out cleanly. There is a mass of 
information here, full credits, greetings and the technical details 
behind the demo. Leonard explains how he coded various screens, how the 
disk reading system was created and you end up feeling really rather 
humbled. There is so much work going on behind this demo that you don't 
get to see "visually" it makes you realise why it took so long to 
complete. In todays world of hard disk loading demos, they don't have 
to worry about half the things you need worry about when running from a 
floppy disk. You can dig deep into the credits system and find those 
who supported the whole thing, kudos to you all.

ˆReset Screen! (Leonard) 

It had to be done. What megademo is complete without one? Hit that 
reset switch and you'll get this screen no matter where in the demo you 
are. It's a TAO chip tune (and therefore bloody great) and 726 4x4 
pixel balls. The balls spin and rotate on a 3 axis world. The entire 
demo is only 3.5k in size, that's optimisation for you! It looks damned 
good too.

Nostalgia-O- is a really nice change from the current trend of "a music 
disk with a couple of nice effects" that's doing the rounds at the 
moment. You actually feel like you get value for your money with this 
demo. There are loads of screens, not one of them isn't worth watching, 
plenty of new music, some nice graphics and some real world record 
breaking screens. It may be a little too technical and less design than 
some people would like, but I think for anyone who has their grass 
roots planted firmly in the raster-distorted world of mega demos from 
the mid to late 80's, this demo will awaken some old feelings for sure. 
Leonard - thank you. Everyone else who contributed to this demo - thank 
you. You've made this reviewer a very happy guy indeed.

Peace.

Richard 
Feb. 99
 


